 =Erebus= (Erʹebus), son Chaos, gods Hades, sometimes alluded representing infernal regions. =Ergatis= (Ergaʹtis). name given Minerva. means work-woman, given goddess credited invented spinning weaving. =Erictheus= (Ericʹtheus), fourth King Athens, son Vulcan. =Erinnys= (Erinʹnys). Greek name Furies. means Disturber Mind. =Erisichthon= (Erisichʹthon) punished perpetual hunger defiled groves Ceres, cut sacred oaks. =Eros= (Erʹos). Greek god love. =Erostratus= (Erosʹtratus). rascal burnt temple Diana Ephesus, thereby hoping make name immortal. =Erycina= (Erycʹina). name Venus, Mount Eryx Sicily. =Erythreos= (Erythreʹos). Grecian name horses Sol'chariot. =Esculapius= (Esculaʹpius), see Aesculapius. =Eta= (Eʹta), see Aeetes. =Ethon= (Eʹthon), horses drew chariot Sol--sun. word Greek, signifies hot. =Etna= (Etʹna). volcanic mountain, beneath , according Virgil, buried giant Typhon, breathes forth devouring flames. =Eudromos= (Euʹdromos). name Actaeon'hounds. =Eulalon= (Euʹlalon), names Apollo. =Eumenides= (Eumeʹnides), name Furies, meaning mild, referring time approved Minerva. =Euphrosyne= (Euphroʹsyne), Graces, see Graces. "Come, thou goddess fair free, heaven ycleped Euphrosyne." Milton. =Eurus= (Euʹrus). east wind. son Aeolus. =Euryale= (Euryʹale) Gorgons, daughter Phorcus Ceto. =Eurydice= (Eurydʹice), wife Orpheus, killed serpent wedding night. "yet golden verge day begun. Orpheus (unhappy lord), Eurydice life restored, beheld, lost, undone." F. Lewis. =Eurythion= (Eurythʹion). -headed dragon. See Geryon. =Euterpe= (Euʹterpe), Muses, patroness instrumental music. word means agreeable. =Euvyhe= (Euʹvyhe), expression meaning "Well done, son." Jupiter frequently addressed son Bacchus words phrase last became names. =Evening Star=, see Hesperus. =Evil=, see Cacodaemon. =Evils=, see Pandora. =Eye=, , see Cyclops Glaukopis. =Fame= poetical deity, represented wings blowing trumpet. temple dedicated Romans. =Fate=, see Nereus. =Fates=, =Parcae=, daughters Necessity. names Clotho, held distaff; Lachesis, turned spindle; Atropos, cut thread fatal shears. =Faun.= rural divinity, half man half goat. similar Satyrs. Fauns attended god Pan, Satyrs attended Bacchus. =Favonius= (Favoʹnius). wind favorable vegetation, , Zephyr--west wind. "... Time run smoother, till Favonius reinspire frozen earth, clothe fresh attire lily rose, neither sowed spun." Milton. =Fays.= "yellow-skirted Fays Fly night-steeds, Leaving moon-loved maze." Milton. =Feasts=, see Comus. =Febris= (Feʹbris) (fever), evil deities, worshiped might harm. =Februus= (Febʹruus). name Pluto, part funeral rites consisted purifications. =Feronia= (Feroʹnia), Roman goddess orchards, patroness enfranchised slaves. authors think Feronia Juno. =Fertility=, see Lupercus. =Festivals=, see Thalia. =Fidelity=, see Iolaus. =Fides= (Fiʹdes), goddess faith honesty, temple Capitol Rome. =Fine Arts=, see Minerva. =Fire=, see Salamander, Vesta, Vulcan. =Fire Insurance=, see Canopus. =Fisherman=, see Glaucus. =Flath-innis= (Flathʹ-ʹnis), Celtic mythology, Paradise. =Fleece, Golden=, see Golden Fleece, Argonauts, Jason. =Flies=, see Muscarius. =Flocks=, see Pales (goddess pastures). =Flora= (Floʹra), goddess flowers gardens, wife Zephyrus. enjoyed perpetual youth. Grecian name Chloris. =Floralia= (Floraʹlia) licentious games instituted honor goddess Flora. =Flowers=, see Flora, Chloris, Hortensis, Zephyrus. =Flute=, see Marsyas. =Fortuna= (Fortuʹna), goddess fortune, temple erected Servius Tullius. supposed able bestow riches poverty mankind, esteemed potent ancient goddesses. usually represented standing wheel, bandage eyes, holding cornucopia. =Fraud=, evil deities, represented goddess human face serpent'body, end tail scorpion'sting. lived river Cocytus, nothing head ever seen. =Freyr= (Freyʹr). Scandinavian god fertility peace. patron god Sweden Iceland. =Freyja= (Freyʹja). Scandinavian Venus. goddess love. =Friga= (Friʹga). Saxon goddess earthly enjoyments. name Friday derived . Scandinavian mythology goddess marriage. =Fro.= Scandinavian god tempests winds. =Frogs=, see Clowns Lycia. [Illustration: Fates _See page 54_] =Fruits=, see Ceres, Pomona. =Funerals=, see Libitina, Manes. =Furies, =, daughters Acheron Nox. punishers evil-doers. names Tisiphone, Megaera, Alecto, supposed personify rage, slaughter, envy. =Futurity=, see Cassandra. =Gabriel= (Gaʹbriel), Jewish mythology prince fire thunder, angel death favored people God. =Galataea= (Galataeʹ). sea nymph. Polyphemus, Cyclops, loved , disdained attentions became lover Acis, Sicilian shepherd. =Gallantes= (Gallanʹtes), madmen, Galli (see). =Galli= (Galʹli) priests Cybele used cut arms knives sacrificed, acted like madmen demented people got name Gallantes. =Ganesa= (Ganʹesa). Indian Mercury. god wisdom prudence. =Ganga.= Indian river goddesses. =Ganymede=, beautiful Phrygian youth, son Tros, King Troy. succeeded Hebe office cup-bearer Jupiter. generally represented sitting back flying eagle. =Gardens=, see Pomona (goddess fruit-trees). =Gates=, see Janus. =Gautama= (Gauʹtama) (Buddha). chief deity Burmah. =Genii= domestic divinities. Every man supposed genii accompanying ; brought happiness, misery. =Genitor= (Genʹitor). Lycian name Jupiter. =Geometry=, see Mercury. =Geryon= (Geʹryon) triple-bodied monster lived Gades, numerous flocks guarded Orthos, -headed dog, Eurythion, -headed dragon. guardians destroyed Hercules, cattle taken away. =Gimlet=, see Daedalus. =Girdle=, see Cestus (Venus'). =Glaucus= (Glauʹcus) fisherman became sea-god eating sea-weed, thought invigorated fishes might strengthen . =Glaukopis= (Glaukoʹpis). name given Minerva, blue eyes. =Gnomes= (Gnoʹmes), name given Plato invisible deities supposed inhabit earth. =Gnossis= (Gnosʹsis), name given Ariadne, city Gnossus, Crete. =Goat=, see Iphigenia, Mendes, Venus. =Goat'Feet=, see Capripedes. =Golden Apple=, see Atalanta. =Golden Fleece, =, ram'hide, sometimes described white, times purple golden. given Phryxus, carried Colchis, King